Version 1.1.0 STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS JACKSON PIPELINE COMPANY Effective July 9, 2010
JACKSON PIPELINE COMPANY, an intrastate pipeline operating within the State of Michigan, will engage in the transportation of natural gas on the following terms and conditions:

Section I. Definitions
A. The term Btu (British thermal unit) shall mean the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one (1) pound of water one degree (1) Fahrenheit at sixty degrees (60) Fahrenheit. (Btu is measured on a dry basis at 14.73 Psia.)
B. The term Cubic Foot of Gas shall mean the quantity of Gas which occupies one (1) cubic foot when such Gas is at a temperature of sixty degrees (60) Fahrenheit and at a pressure base of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths (14.73) Psia dry.
C. The term Day shall mean a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours beginning at 10:00 a.m. Eastern clock time or at such other time as may be mutually agreed.
D. The term Delivery Point shall mean a point at the outlet side of Transporters facilities at a point of interconnection between the facilities of Transporter and the facilities of Shipper or its designee.
E. The term Gas shall mean natural gas, manufactured gas or a combination of the two.
F. The term Mcf as used herein, shall be determined by multiplying the number of Cubic Feet of Gas received/delivered during each Day by the factor arrived at by dividing the average Total Heating Value Per Cubic Foot for such Day, on the basis indicated in Section VII.A, hereof, by one million (1,000,000).
G. The term Month shall mean a period beginning at 10:00 a.m. Eastern clock time on the first Day of a calendar month and ending at 10:00 a.m. Eastern clock time on the first Day of the following calendar month.
H. The term Psia shall mean pounds per square inch absolute.
I. The term Receipt Point shall mean a point at the inlet side of Transporters facilities at a point of interconnection between the facilities of Transporter and the facilities of Shipper or its designee.
J. The term Shipper shall mean any party that has executed a transportation agreement for transportation service subject to this Statement of Operating Conditions.
K. The term Transporter shall mean Jackson Pipeline Company.
L. The term Volumes of Gas shall mean quantities of Gas measured in Mcf.
4
Section II. Conditions of Receipt and Delivery
A. Volumes of Gas to be transported hereunder shall be received and delivered at uniform hourly and daily rates of flow. B. In the event the Volumes of Gas received and delivered are not in balance at the end of the term of the transportation service agreement, then a balance shall be achieved as soon as practicable by extending receipts or deliveries, as applicable, at the appropriate Receipt or Delivery Points until such a balance is achieved. C. Transporter is under no obligation to perform transportation hereunder if Eaton Rapids, ANR, CECo or PEPL is unwilling, not obligated to, or unable to receive deliveries hereunder, as the case may be.
Section III. Rates for Section 311 Transportation Service
A. Rates charged for Section 311(a)(2) transportation services shall be negotiated between Transporter and Shipper, but shall not exceed the applicable maximum rates approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (Commission) for the type of Section 311(a)(2) transportation service rendered by Transporter. Transporters maximum rates for Section 311(a)(2) transportation services are reviewed and approved by the Commission in proceedings filed pursuant to the Commissions Regulations at 18 C. F. R. Section 284.123(b)(1)(ii). Transporter reserves the right to seek authorization from the Commission and/or other appropriate agencies, if necessary, to increase, decrease, or restructure the maximum rates in effect at any time as may be found necessary to assure Transporter fair and equitable maximum rates within the meaning of Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA and the Commissions implementing Rules, Regulations, and Orders. Nothing herein contained shall be construed to deny any Shipper any rights they may have under the Commissions rules and regulations, including the right to participate fully in rate proceedings by intervention or otherwise to contest changes in rates in whole or part. Transporter may at any time provide Section 311(a)(2) transportation services at a discount from the maximum rates approved by the Commission. Nothing herein shall obligate or require, or be construed to obligate or require, Transporter to offer or continue such discount. B. Shipper will not be required to provide fuel for any Volumes of Gas transported by Transporter hereunder. 5
Section IV. Scheduling and Notification
Shipper will nominate for transportation hereunder during the Month in accordance with North American Energy Standards Board (NAESB) nomination times. Shipper shall, by telephoning, telecopying, or other electronic means, notify CECos, PEPLs, ANRs or Eaton Rapids Gas Control Transport Coordinator, as appropriate, give at least 24 hours notice of any proposed change of the Volumes of Gas to be transported hereunder.
Section V. Governmental Authorizations
A. This Statement of Operating Conditions and the respective obligations of the parties hereunder are subject to all valid laws, orders, rules and regulations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction, and are conditioned upon the issuance of any governmental agency having jurisdiction of requisite authorizations for Transporter to construct and operate the pipeline facilities and provide the transportation services contemplated herein. B. When requested by Transporter, Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any and all reasonable filing fees required in connection with this transportation service that Transporter is obligated to pay to any governmental authority having jurisdiction.
Section VI. Quality
A. Gas tendered by Shipper for transportation: (a) shall not contain more than 10 parts per million of oxygen; (b) shall be commercially free from objectionable odors, solid or liquid matter, dust, gum or gum-forming constituents which might interfere with its merchantability or cause injury to or interference with proper operation of the lines, regulators, meters or other appliances through which it flows; (c) shall not contain more than 1.0 grain of hydrogen sulphide per one hundred Cubic Feet of Gas; (d) shall not contain more than twenty grains of total sulphur per one hundred Cubic Feet of Gas; (e) shall not at any time have a carbon dioxide content in excess of two percent (2%) by volume; and (f) shall not contain an amount of moisture which at any time exceeds seven pounds per million Cubic Feet of Gas. B. The Gas shall have a Total Heating Value Per Cubic Foot of not less than 950 Btus nor more than 1,200 Btus. The term Total Heating Value Per Cubic Foot shall mean the number of Btus produced by the combustion, at constant pressure, of one (1) anhydrous (dry) Cubic Foot of Gas, with air of the same pressure and temperature as the Gas when the products of combustion are cooled to the initial temperature of the Gas and air and when the water formed by the combustion is condensed to the liquid state. This definition applies regardless of the equipment used to determine 6
the Total Heating Value Per Cubic Foot.
C. If the Gas tendered or caused to be tendered for transportation shall fail at any time to conform to any of the specifications provided for in Sections A or B above, then Transporter shall notify Shipper of the deficiency and thereupon may refuse to accept delivery until such deficiency is corrected. The remedies herein provided are in addition to any and all other remedies at law or in equity to which either party may be entitled.
Section VII. Measurement
A. Total Heating Value Per Cubic Foot . The Total Heating Value per Cubic Foot of the Gas received and delivered hereunder shall be determined by means of a monthly average of daily Gas analysis obtained by use of a Gas Chromatograph and installed so that it may properly record the Total Heating Value per Cubic Foot of the Gas at the Receipt and Delivery Point(s). Such Chromatograph shall be checked at least once each Month to assure its proper operation and accuracy. An appropriate certified Gas sample of known heat content shall be used to check the Chromatograph accuracy. B. Computations of Volume from Meter Readings and Registrations : The Volume of Gas received or delivered hereunder shall be determined in the manner specified in AGA Gas Measurement Committee Report No. 3 (AGA Report No. 3"), as such publication may be revised from time to time, or in accordance with other reports and publications which are mutually acceptable to Transporter and Shipper. C. Flowing Temperature : The flowing temperature of Gas received and delivered hereunder shall be determined by means of a standard recording thermometer or other instrument of standard manufacture accepted in the industry. The flowing temperature used in determining the flowing temperature factor for each record shall be the arithmetical average of the temperatures shown by the recording instrument during the period of time when Gas is passing through the meter.
D. Specific Gravity : The specific gravity of the Gas received and delivered hereunder shall be determined by a Gas Chromatograph installed so that it may properly record the specific gravity of the Gas at the Receipt and Delivery Point(s). The arithmetical average of the hourly specific gravity recording each Day shall be deemed to be the specific gravity of the Gas for that Day. Such instrument shall be checked at least once each Month or at intervals mutually agreed to by Transporter and Shipper. E. Supercompressibility : Adjustment for the effect of supercompressibility for Gas received and delivered hereunder shall be made according to the provisions of AGA Report #8 as such publication may be revised from time to time, or of other reports and publications which are mutually acceptable to Transporter and Shipper, for the average conditions of pressure, flowing temperature and specific gravity at which the Gas was measured during the period under 7
consideration and with the proportionate values of carbon dioxide and nitrogen in the Gas received and delivered included in the computation of the applicable supercompressibility factors. Transporter and Shipper shall exercise due diligence in obtaining initial carbon dioxide and nitrogen fraction values and shall obtain subsequent values of these components quarterly or at other intervals mutually agreeable. F. Assumed Atmospheric Pressure : The average absolute atmospheric (barometric) pressure shall be assumed to be fourteen and four-tenths (14.4) Psia irrespective of actual elevation or location of the Receipt and Delivery Point(s) above sea level or variations in actual barometric pressure from time to time.
Section VIII. Measuring Equipment
A. Measuring Equipment : The Gas which Shipper delivers or causes CECo, ANR, and PEPL to deliver to Transporter hereunder and which Transporter redelivers to CECo, ANR, and PEPL for the account of Shipper shall be measured by measuring equipment owned, and installed by Transporter and operated by Transporter or its designee. The measuring equipment shall be of one- way flow designs and of a type generally accepted by the natural gas industry for the measurement of Gas rates of flow and pressures expected to exist at the Receipt and Delivery Point(s). When orifice meters are used, they shall be of a type specified and recommended in AGA Report No. 3, as such publication may be revised from time to time, or of other reports and publications which are mutually agreeable to Transporter and Shipper, and the construction and installation shall be in accordance with the recommendations and specifications set forth in said report. B. Access to Measuring Equipment, Test and Records : Shipper shall have access to all measuring equipment at all reasonable hours, but the reading, calibrating and adjusting thereof and the changing of charts shall be done by Transporter or its designees. Further, Shipper shall have the right to be present at the time of any installing, testing, reading, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, calibrating or adjusting done in connection with the measuring equipment used in determining the volumes of receipts and deliveries hereunder, and Shipper shall be given reasonable notice thereof in order that it may be present. The records and measurement data from such measuring equipment shall remain the property of Transporter, but Transporter, upon request, shall submit to Shipper such records and measurement data, or reproductions thereof, together with calculations therefrom, for inspection and verification. Original records or measurement data so submitted will be returned to Transporter within ten (10) Days after receipt thereof. C. Check Measuring Equipment : Shipper may install, maintain and operate and remove, at its own expense, such check measuring equipment as it shall desire at the Receipt and Delivery Point(s), and Transporter shall provide a suitable site therefore and allow Shipper free access to and use of the site; provided that such equipment shall be installed, maintained and operated so as not to interfere with the operation or maintenance of Transporters measuring equipment at the Receipt and Delivery Point(s). Transporter shall have free access to the check measuring equipment at all 8
reasonable hours. The reading, calibrating and adjusting thereof and any changing of charts shall be done by Shipper, but Transporter shall be given reasonable prior notice thereof. D. Failure of Measuring Equipment : Transporter and Shipper agree that if for any reason Transporters measuring equipment is out of service or out of repair so that the Volume of Gas delivered is not correctly indicated by the reading thereof, the Gas delivered through the period such measuring equipment is out of service or out of repair shall be estimated and agreed upon on the basis of the best data available, using the first of the following methods which is feasible: (i) by using the registration of any check meter or meters if installed and accurately registering; or (ii) by using the registration of the Eaton Rapids meter(s) and the CECo interchange meters, as appropriate, if installed and accurately registering; or (iii) by correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test or mathematical calculation; or (iv) by estimating the volume of delivery by deliveries during preceding periods under similar conditions when the measuring equipment was registering accurately. E. Measuring Equipment Tests : Transporter shall cause the accuracy of the measuring equipment to be verified at least each Month. F. Correction of Measuring Equipment Errors : If upon any test, Transporters measuring equipment is found to be inaccurate by two percent (2%) or less volumetrically (chromatograph/calorimeter 0.5% or less): (A) previous readings of such equipment shall be considered correct in computing the deliveries of Gas, but such equipment shall be adjusted properly at once to record accurately; (B) any previous readings of such equipment shall be corrected to zero error for any period which is known definitely or agreed upon by Transporter and Shipper; but if the period is not known definitely or agreed upon, such correction shall be for a period covering the last half of the time elapsed since the date of the last test, but not exceeding a period of sixteen (16) Days. G. Preservation of Records : Shipper and Transporter agree to preserve, for a period of at least three (3) years, or such longer period as any jurisdictional agency having authority may require, all test data, measurement data and other similar records. H. Improvements in Gas Measuring Techniques : If at any time a new method or technique is developed with respect to Gas measurement or the determination of the factors used in such Gas measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted upon mutual agreement of Transporter and Shipper and with the concurrence of Eaton Rapids. 9
I. Presumption of Correctness: All meter readings, measurement data and all reports and statements of Volumes of Gas received or delivered by Transporter shall be conclusively presumed correct unless contested by either party hereto within one year of the date such report or statement is rendered.
Section IX. Responsibility During Transportation
Transporter and Shipper shall be responsible for its own equipment and facilities and the Gas covered hereby when delivered to or located on its side of the Receipt and Delivery Points. The party having responsibility for the Gas shall remain responsible for same until it receives/delivers the same to or for the account of the other party. Each party also warrants to the other that it will, at the time of receipt or delivery hereunder, by such party to or for the account of the other, have good title or good right to make such receipt or delivery and further warrants for itself, its successors and assigns that such Gas shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and claims whatsoever of those not parties hereto. With respect to any adverse claim that may arise to said Gas or to royalties, taxes, license fees or charges thereon, the party delivering or causing the delivery of the Gas shall indemnify and save the receiving party harmless from all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses and expenses arising from or out of such adverse claim provided that the receiving party gives the other prompt notice of such adverse claim.
Section X. Statements and Payments
A. On or before the first (1 st ) Day of the Month, Transporter will render a statement to Shipper for service provided hereunder for such Month. B. Shipper shall pay to Transporter, on or before the twenty-first (21 st ) Day of each Month, the amount billed by Transporter in the statement for said Month. All such payments shall be made in the form of immediately available funds directed to a bank account designated by Transporter or by check mailed to Transporter and received not later than the twenty-first (21 st ) Day of said Month. If the last Day for paying an invoice hereunder is not a banking Day, the time of payment shall be extended through the next banking Day. C. Should Shipper fail to pay the full amount of any statement rendered by Transporter as herein provided when such amount is due, all such unpaid amounts shall accrue interest at a rate equal to the rate of interest announced by Citibank, N.A., New York from time to time as its prime rate of interest, plus two percentage points, or at the highest legal rate of interest, whichever is less (the Default Rate). D. If Shippers failure to pay the amount of any statement rendered by Transporter continues for thirty (30) Days after payment is due, Transporter shall have the right, but not the 10
obligation, to suspend further service to Shipper until such amount is paid, or to terminate Shippers transportation agreement without further notice, provided, however, that if Shipper in good faith shall either dispute the amount of any such statement or parts thereof or present a counterclaim or offset against the same, and at any time thereafter, within fifteen (15) Days after demand made by Transporter shall furnish a good and sufficient surety bond, in the amount and with sureties satisfactory to Transporter, conditioned upon the payment of any amounts ultimately found due upon such statement after a final determination, which may be reached by agreement, or by judgment of the courts, then such statement shall not be deemed to be due within the meaning of this Section unless and until default be made in the conditions of such bond. If Transporter shall require Shipper to furnish such a bond, Transporter shall institute appropriate proceedings to resolve the dispute with respect to which the bond has been furnished within one (1) year after the date of the statement in dispute. The foregoing remedy shall be in addition to any other remedies Transporter may have, at law or in equity, with respect to Shippers failure to pay the amount of any such statements. E. If presentation of a statement by Transporter is delayed after the first (1 st ) Day of the Month, then the time for payment shall be extended correspondingly, unless Shipper is responsible for such delay. F. If Shipper shall find at any time within twelve (12) Months after the date of any statement rendered by Transporter that it has been overcharged in the amount billed in such statement, and if Shipper shall have paid said overcharge and shall have made a claim therefore within sixty (60) Days from the date of discovery thereof, Transporter shall verify and refund the principal of any such overcharge within thirty (30) Days, with interest thereon at the Default Rate.
G. If Transporter shall find at any time within twelve (12) Months after the date of any statement rendered by it that there has been an undercharge in the amount billed in such statement, it may submit a statement for such undercharge and Shipper shall pay the same without interest, but this provision shall not preclude Shipper from disputing the amount of such statement or the assertion that there has been an undercharge. H. Each party shall have the right at all reasonable times to examine the books, records and charts of the other party, to the extent necessary to verify such partys compliance with this Statement of Operating Conditions. I. Transporter shall not be required to commence service or to continue to provide service under this Statement of Operating Conditions in the event that Shipper is or has become insolvent or fails to demonstrate credit worthiness to the reasonable satisfaction of Transporter in light of previous experience and information available when requested by Transporter; provided, however, that Shipper may receive service if Shipper deposits with Transporter and maintains, in a prepaid account, an amount equal to the charges that would be due for three (3) Months service or otherwise furnishes good and sufficient security, as reasonably determined by Transporter, of a continuing nature and in an amount equal to such amounts which would be due. Transporter may, at its option and without waiving any rights or remedies it may have, suspend further service hereunder until such security is provided. 11
Section XI. Force Majeure
A. The term Force Majeure as used herein shall mean any act, omission or circumstance occasioned by or as a consequence of any acts of God, strikes, lockouts, acts of the public enemy, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, washouts, arrests and restraints of the government (either Federal or state, civil or military), civil disturbances, explosions, shutdowns for the purpose of necessary repairs, alterations, relocation or construction of facilities, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe, the necessity for testing (as required by governmental authority or as deemed necessary by Transporter for the safe or proper operation of its facilities), laws or orders or rules or regulations or acts of any court or governmental authority, and any other cause, whether of the kind enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such party is unable to prevent or overcome. Failure to prevent or settle any strike or strikes shall not be considered to be a matter within the control of the party claiming suspension. B. Anything in this Section to the contrary notwithstanding, in the event either party hereto is rendered unable to perform, wholly or in part, by Force Majeure, then, on such partys giving notice and full particulars of such Force Majeure in writing to the other party, as soon as practicable after the occurrence of the cause relied upon, the obligations of the party giving such notice, so far as it is affected by such Force Majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of the inability so caused, but for no longer period. Such causes or contingencies affecting the performance hereunder by either party hereto, however, shall not relieve it of liability in the event of its failure to use diligence to remedy the situation and to remove the cause in an adequate manner and with all reasonable dispatch. Shipper will not be obligated to pay a monthly demand charge in the event, and to the extent, that service hereunder requested by Shipper during any one or more Days, was not rendered by Transporter due to Force Majeure affecting Transporter, and in any such event, the monthly demand charge as otherwise computed hereunder shall be reduced by an amount equal to the sum of all such Days deficiencies multiplied by the demand charge.
Section XII. Assignments
Any transaction entered into that is governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the successors, assigns, personal representatives, and heirs of the respective Shipper and Transporter. No assignment of such transaction, in whole or in part, shall be made by Shipper without the prior written consent of Transporter, which consent will not be unreasonably withheld, provided, however, Shipper may transfer its interest to any affiliate by assignment, merger or otherwise without prior written consent of Transporter. Transporter may assign its interests to the partner of Transporter or to affiliates of such partner without consent of the 12
Shipper. No assignment that is not permitted under this section shall relieve the assignor of any of its obligations pursuant to this Statement of Operating Conditions unless the other party so agrees in writing. 13
